      <h2>The Business Impact of Strong Internal Linking</h2>
      <p>Internal linking is not just an SEO tactic — it is a business strategy. When done well, it achieves three outcomes simultaneously: better search rankings, longer user sessions, and higher conversion rates.</p>
      <p><strong>Search rankings improve</strong> because internal links pass topical authority and help Google understand which pages are most important. A page with 15 relevant internal links from high-quality content typically outranks a similar page with no internal links — even if the content quality is identical. Google uses links as a proxy for importance.</p>
      <p><strong>User sessions lengthen</strong> because relevant internal links give readers a natural path to explore more content. According to a 2025 HubSpot analysis, blog posts with 5+ contextual internal links have 37% longer average session durations than posts with no internal links. Longer sessions signal quality to search engines and increase the chance of conversion.</p>
      <p><strong>Conversion rates increase</strong> because internal links guide users through the buyer's journey. A blog reader learning about "signs of a roof leak" who clicks an internal link to "free roof inspection" is significantly more likely to become a lead than a reader who finishes the article with no clear next step. Internal links turn content into funnels.</p>

